DESCRIPTION:Join Deaf artist and practitioner Zoya  for a guided walkthrough of the exhibition warrior garments. \n\nReflecting on her journey of resilience\, passion and her aim to create inclusive spaces for the Deaf community\, Zoya brings forward the voices of Deaf women through her interpretation of the exhibition. \n
DTEND:20260620T220000Z
DTSTART:20260620T213000Z
SUMMARY:Warrior Garments Through the Lens of Zoya
UID:1308@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/warrior-garments-through-the-lens-of-zoya/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/maxresdefault.jpg
CATEGORIES:Film Screenings,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260609T072024Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: EH Filmes\nJoin us for a screening of Margaret Mee and the Moonflower\, a documentary chronicling the life and work of British botanist and artist Margaret Mee. Directed by Malu de Martino\, the film follows Mee’s expeditions to the Amazon basin\, where she meticulously documented rare flora—including the elusive night-blooming moonflower (Selenicereus grandiflorus)—through detailed botanical illustrations.\n\nPresented alongside MAP’s Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire exhibition\, this screening celebrates Mee’s legacy as both an artist and conservation advocate.
DTEND:20260614T110000Z
DTSTART:20260614T093000Z
SUMMARY:Margaret Mee and the Moonflower
UID:1305@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/margaret-mee-and-the-moonflower/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/HP-Slider-Images-Mobile-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260604T073620Z
DESCRIPTION:What does vulnerability look like? What does care feel like?\nThese are the questions that artist afra eisma leaves us with in warrior garments.\n\nJoin us for the final session of reflective feminist reading sessions\, developed in collaboration with Zubaan and facilitated by Laxmi Murthy. Together\, we will explore gender-based violence—its lived realities\, and the possibilities of resistance\, solidarity\, and healing. Through stories\, essays\, and personal reflections\, you are invited to engage with the exhibition at your own pace\, in a space that encourages listening\, sharing\, and care.\n\nNote: This is the final session in a series presented alongside Warrior Garments. Reading materials for each will be shared after registration.\n\nTrigger Warning: The sessions may include discussions on sexual violence.
DTEND:20260621T073000Z
DTSTART:20260621T053000Z
SUMMARY:Holding Space: Feminist Reading Circle
UID:1302@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/holding-space-feminist-reading-circle-3/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Untitled-design-10.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260609T115613Z
DESCRIPTION:Magnolia campbellii H.f. &amp\; T\; Illustrations of Himalayan Plants\; Author &amp\; Artist: Joseph Dalton Hooker\; Lithographer: Walter Hood Fitch\; 1855\; Image courtesy of the Missouri Botanical Garden Library via the Biodiversity Heritage Library\nIn this walk\, Abhishek Khan traces the backstory of the few surviving—and many lost—flowers and plants that were painted in Lalbagh. As we observe the fragrant flowers and leaves around us\, we learn how today's botanical collection are a product of the aesthetics established by colonial empire\, continuing to influence what we see in gardens today. \n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260614T040000Z
DTSTART:20260614T023000Z
SUMMARY:A Fragrance Walk at Lalbagh Botanical Garden
UID:1297@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/a-fragrance-walk-at-lalbagh-botanical-garden/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/image-3-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260608T084534Z
DESCRIPTION:Botanical gardens have long operated as sites of inquiry\, collection\, and visualisation\, underpinning practices of classification and production of botanical illustration. In this walkthrough and workshop\, we re-examine historic botanical gardens within broader frameworks of imperial science and cultural production.\n\nForegrounding orchids\, we trace the emergence of nineteenth‑century Victorian orchid mania\, engage with rare varieties represented in the exhibition\, and reconsider Indian botanical knowledge and labour in these visual records.\n\nThe workshop concludes with a lecture-demonstration in orchid cultivation by The Orchid Society of Karnataka (TOSKAR)\, connecting these archival documents to contemporary horticultural practice and expertise.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.\n
DTEND:20260613T080000Z
DTSTART:20260613T060000Z
SUMMARY:Paper Orchids\, Living Blooms
UID:1304@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/paper-orchids-living-blooms/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Abhishek-Khan-is-a-research-based-artist-designer-and-storyteller-who-works-under-the-pen-name-Hand-Jobs-Inc.-His-practice-explores-the-relationships-between-people-memory-and-the-natural-worl-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260609T115523Z
DESCRIPTION:Untitled\, Durgaprasad Bandi\,2022\, Cyanotype\, MAC.02155\nThis workshop introduces participants to cyanotype process through direct engagement with materials\, light\, and composition. Rooted in the legacy of early photographic image-making\, the session moves from technical understanding to exploratory making.\n\nBeginning with an introduction to the history and context of cyanotype\, participants then prepare coated surfaces\, compose images using botanical specimens\, and expose prints using sunlight and UV sources. \n\nOn experimentation with form\, layering\, and variations in exposure and washing\, participants understand how the process responds to material and environmental conditions. \n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260613T120000Z
DTSTART:20260613T090000Z
SUMMARY:Prints in Blue
UID:1299@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/prints-in-blue/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/NOCTURNES-new-still-4-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260604T072821Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Metamorphosis Film Junction\nThe workshop evolves from the core ideas of the film Nocturnes. We will together experience\, discuss\, and go deeper into the interface between duration and attention through a range of guided individual and group exercises: listening to field recordings\, viewing film excerpts\, taking photographs and videos\, and recording sounds. You will have an opportunity to explore and interpret the world around you through images\, sounds\, and unexpected ways in which they interact and speak to each other. No prior technical knowledge is required. All we ask is for you to be present with an open and curious mind.\n\nAttending the screening of Nocturnes on 19 June is highly recommended. \n\nThis event is held in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. 
DTEND:20260620T083000Z
DTSTART:20260620T043000Z
SUMMARY:Between Seeing and Listening
UID:1301@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/between-seeing-and-listening/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/PAT03836-1.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260611T115024Z
DESCRIPTION:This hands-on stitching workshop introduces participants to the basics of hand stitching\, crochet\, and simple craft-making techniques. Led by Zoya\, the session focuses on creativity\, patience\, and self-expression through textiles. Participants will explore how everyday materials can be transformed into meaningful handmade pieces. The workshop is designed to be inclusive and accessible\, encouraging participants of all skill levels to learn\, create\, and connect.
DTEND:20260621T083000Z
DTSTART:20260621T053000Z
SUMMARY:Stitching Stories
UID:1309@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/stitching-stories/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Screenshot-2026-06-11-183344.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260611T130432Z
DESCRIPTION:Ever thought of how museums fix old letters\, sketches or books without causing a lot of damage? Can a simple glue fix the tear? Would you like to know? Come and ask a conservator! \n\nConservators play a vital role in keeping culture and heritage alive for future generations. Join us for an interactive workshop with Nayana from the Conservation Department and get a behind-the-scenes look at the conservation processes used at MAP. Discover what a career in conservation means\, look at the materials and techniques used by industry professionals and learn practical methods to preserve your own treasured items and artworks.\n\nThis session is conducted as part of our initiatives for young people (18 - 25 years old) to engage with and explore a career in the arts and culture sector.
DTEND:20260627T083000Z
DTSTART:20260627T053000Z
SUMMARY:Conservation Uncovered!
UID:1310@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/conservation-uncovered/
